<font color="#FF0000">OLDER BOOKS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan 25 18:31:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
One of my favorite fiction writers is John M. Del Vecchio.  His two books, &quot;The 13th Valley&quot; and &quot;For The Sake Of All Living Things&quot; should be read by all.  The latter book is a must for anyone who wishes to truly understand the Cambodian holocaust. <br><br>
While I was in DaNang, I read Chester L. Cooper's book &quot;The Lost Crusade, American in Vietnam.&quot;  It covers the war from 1945 to 1970, and has a detailed chronology for that period.  Another that I read in-country is &quot;Our Own Worst Enemy.&quot;  I don't know the author, but it detailed the graft and corruption within the Vietnamese government, and also how our committments hindered the war effort.  For instance, the requirement for Vietnamese longshoresmen led to a great loss of goods shipped to South Vietnam. <br><br>
Two others I bought in-country, which provided an interesting account of the Vietnamese people, were &quot;Vietnam, Our Beloved Land&quot; by Nguyen Cao Dam and Tran Cao Linh; and &quot;Face of North Vietnam&quot; by Marc Riboud, text by Philippe DeVillers.
